            . I live in <placeName id="t18220911-115-crimeloc629">Plumtree-street, in the parish of St. Giles</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18220911-115-crimeloc629" type="placeName" value="Plumtree-street, in the parish of St. Giles"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18220911-115-crimeloc629" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18220911-115-off627 t18220911-115-crimeloc629"></join>. I occupy the back room of the second floor of 
               <persName id="t18220911-115-person1142">
                  William 
                  Morgan
               <interp inst="t18220911-115-person1142" type="surname" value="Morgan"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220911-115-person1142" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220911-115-person1142" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's house. On Monday, the 26th of August, about five o'clock in the evening, I was at work in the shop below - and in consequence of what was said, I went up into my room, and found the door broken open. I had locked it half an hour before. I missed the property stated in the indictment, which is worth about 3 l., or more; the suit of clothes were nearly new, and cost 6 l. 4 s. I had them about fifteen months, but only wore them on Sunday. I value them altogether, at 3 l. I am sure I could not buy them for that. I went to Bow-street on the 27th, and saw the prisoner with one of the shirts on his back, which I am positive is mine.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18220911-115-person1143">
                  JOHN 
                  PURTON
               <interp inst="t18220911-115-person1143" type="surname" value="PURTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220911-115-person1143" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18220911-115-person1143" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I took the shirt off the prisoner's back; he resisted very much. I was obliged to knock him down, and get two more to pinion him.</p>
               <p>(Shirt produced and sworn to.)</p>
